snippet.title: Coleborn's hopes of qualifying for world tour shaken
snippet.content: SURFING: Mitch Coleborn's hopes of earning a berth on next year's world tour were seriously dented at California on Tuesday, when he made an early exit from a crucial qualifying series event. The 30-year-old, who has been on the fringes of the globe's main circuit for years, was eliminated from the Vans US Open of Surfing at iconic Huntington Beach in round two. It's one of the highest rated events on the schedule - with 10,000 points on offer - so the Wurtulla product missed a prime chance to improve on his 22nd ranking. The top 10 on the season-ending QS standings, not including surfers who are also in the top 22 of the world tour, will claim spots on next year's championship roster. There are three more 10,000-point events left. Fellow Sunshine Coaster Keely Andrew was scheduled to resume her world tour campaign on Tuesday night, also at California. It's the sixth stop on a 10-stop calendar.
